## High Quality PDF Output ##
The output of LaTeX is a PDF and it is of great quality. Unlike the majority of
resumes that will use 12pt Times New Roman and will use mediocre layout, a LaTeX
document will have full justification, correct spacing and aesthetically
pleasing line breaking. In addition the output is a PDF which is superior than
an HTML document or a Microsoft Word document for a few reasons.

First a PDF can be viewed on any operating system and it is guaranteed to look
the same on all of them. Unlike an HTML document which might be subject to the
viewer's browser or other factors. In addition a PDF enables me to embed fonts
so I can select an esoteric font and know it will display correctly on every
computer. It will also print correctly.

The last reason ensures that your resume will look nicer compared to the 95% of
resumes that use Arial/Helvetica or Times New Roman.

## Basic Template ##
The full [source] of my resume is on my github, but it isn't for everyone. To
get you started you should start with the following packages:

~~~ {.latex}
\documentclass[10pt,letterpaper]{article}
\usepackage[margin=0.75in]{geometry}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{microtype}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{tgpagella}
\usepackage{enumitem}
\pagestyle{empty}
~~~

Most of these packages are useful default packages for any document but a few of
these are very important for a resume. First the `hyperref` package is essential
for creating links, it provides a `\href` macro that allows your PDF to have
clickable links when viewed on a computer. The `tgpagella` package sets the font
to [TeX Gyre Pagella](http://www.tug.dk/FontCatalogue/tgpagella/) which is
a very nice serif font. The `microtype` package adds many little niceties to
the output of the document such as optimizing interword spacing and adding
additional kerning. The `empty` page style removes page numbers which are not
appropriate for a resume.

